				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/qntm" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(571081); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=571081&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227484" alt="qntm" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=571081)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/qntm" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(571081); return false;" >qntm</a></span> <span class="odate time_1555163535 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">13 Apr 2019 13:52</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4217871">
									

<p>Apologies for the ambiguity. &quot;The Escapee&quot; shouldn't be interpreted to mean that SCP-3125 escaped from some other location and arrived here. I called SCP-3125 &quot;the Escapee&quot; because, despite what it might appear from the exterior SCP entry in <a href="/scp-3125">SCP-3125</a>, the Foundation has not successfully contained it. When you go into the containment unit and read the real entry, you realise that it is not in the box, but in fact still at large. It has, as it were, escaped containment (&quot;escaped&quot; meaning &quot;eluded&quot; here, not in the sense that it was ever successfully contained).</p>
<p>(Also please note that, the Foundation/Antimemetics Division, in-universe, does not refer to SCP-3125 as &quot;the Escapee&quot;. SCP codenames like &quot;the Escapee&quot; and &quot;the Sculpture&quot; and so on aren't generally canon as far as I know.)</p>
<p>So, does SCP-3125 have a &quot;home dimension&quot; as such? Maybe, but maybe not.</p>

